title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum on 1993-12-18
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, They Love Each Other, Spoonful, Friend Of The Devil, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Tennessee Jed, Easy Answers, Deal

Set 2

Way to Go Home, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Playin' In The Band-> Uncle John's Band-> Jerry, Phil, Billy and Mickey-> Drums-> Space-> I Need A Miracle-> Stella Blue-> One More Saturday Night, E: Box Of Rain

reviews.review_text: Recording Info Neumann KM140 -> Aerco p/s. I can't remember if we used a Sony D-10 Pro or Sony SBM-1 -> D-8 as lead deck. I'm not digging up my Master DAT to check but it was one or the other

Another good 1993 performance ... Hi GD folks,   I recall this show from back in the day; I had a DAT copy of this source and another one;  a good transfer from the master always makes a difference.  1993, in my opinion, was probably the last consistent year from the Grateful Dead.  It seemed like a new energy and approach came with this year.  The addition of a new in ear monitor system ( a industry standard today paved by the GD as usual ! ) was added along with the benefit of  new prominence on the vocals. 

A solid 1st set with a great song selection but the 2nd set really shines.  A really nice pre drums set with a majestic jam at the end of Uncle John's Band really show the GD still want to deliver a great live experience.  

Of course,  this show probably will not be a commercial release since it's not the old classic GD but it is a nice well played concert with heart and soul.  One of the better audience sources out there in my opinion.  ( I don't think this one has the SBM "super bit mapping" by Sony,  please correct me if I am incorrect, but Sony didn't make a portable deck or accessory with SBM back then? )

great recording/good show This is a rare excellent post-91 audience recording and a nice superior '93 show as well.  It has that pleasant, dreamy quality that makes a first set fly by and an ear-candy Space you don't want to end.  The Uncle Johns>jam is the big highlight but the Way to Go Home is strong and the Easy Answers is pretty good too.
